  "opening_lines": [
    {
      "line": 1,
      "text": "| ECOSPHERE:"
    },
    {
      "line": 2,
      "text": "A SEALED GLOBE THAT LIVES FOREVER, P. 28"
    },
    {
      "line": 3,
      "text": "ANARCHY WILL BAKER THE"
    },
    {
      "line": 4,
      "text": "THAT WORKS: DEEPER HACKERS"
    },
    {
      "line": 7,
      "text": "ITALY IN NICARAGUA CONFERENCE"
    },
    {
      "line": 13,
      "text": "EARTH"
    },
    {
      "line": 16,
      "text": "No. 46 MAY 1985 $3 (No Advertising)"
    },
    {
      "line": 22,
      "text": "by Charles Pappas"
    },
    {
      "line": 25,
      "text": "An otherwise pleasant Charles"
    },
    {
      "line": 26,
      "text": "Pappas insists on discussing hurt,"
    },
    {
      "line": 27,
      "text": "badness, evil, and our taboo"
    },
    {
      "line": 28,
      "text": "against discussing these. His"
    },
    {
      "line": 29,
      "text": "“Bad Seeds” (CQ Summer 1984,"
    },
    {
      "line": 30,
      "text": "p. 60) dragged us over to face"
    },
    {
      "line": 31,
      "text": "pure nastiness, and said we were"
    },
    {
      "line": 32,
      "text": "responsible. Now he’s hovering"
    },
    {
      "line": 33,
      "text": "over the dead. In between"
    },
    {
      "line": 34,
      "text": "Journeys to war-torn countries"
    },
    {
      "line": 35,
      "text": "he’s a counselor at a group home"
    },
    {
      "line": 36,
      "text": "for disabled adults in LaCrosse,"
    },
    {
      "line": 37,
      "text": "Wisconsin. -Kevin Kelly"
    },
    {
      "line": 40,
      "text": "Dear Stewart,"
    },
    {
      "line": 43,
      "text": "Before and after I traveled to Northern Ireland I read CQ’s"
    },
    {
      "line": 44,
      "text": "write-ups on death. Plenty more to add."
    },
    {
      "line": 47,
      "text": "Autopsies (CQ, Spring 1984, p. 4) and New Orleans funerals"
    },
    {
      "line": 48,
      "text": "(CQ, Fall 1984, p. 38) tell you a lot about death - death and"
    },
    {
      "line": 49,
      "text": "its attendants. So does war; I’ve had a look-see at two. I"
    },
    {
      "line": 50,
      "text": "learned there is little difference between my writing about"
    },
    {
      "line": 51,
      "text": "war and my ministering to the dying in a nursing home:"
    },
    {
      "line": 53,
      "text": "I attend what's left over. Tolstoy looked at the misery around"
    },
    {
      "line": 54,
      "text": "himself and asked, “What then must we do?” He should"
    },
    {
      "line": 55,
      "text": "have known better, the old geezer. Whether the bodies had"
    },
    {
      "line": 56,
      "text": "bullets or [Vs in them, the reader-over-my-shoulder kept"
    },
    {
      "line": 57,
      "text": "track of what it all meant. I wanted to know. I wanted to see."
    },
    {
      "line": 60,
      "text": "Camaraderie, intense experiences, the passion to witness . . ."
    },
    {
      "line": 61,
      "text": "these are dependable explanations for a curiosity about war,"
    },
    {
      "line": 64,
      "text": "Gustave Dore"
    },
    {
      "line": 67,
      "text": "There is a connection"
    },
    {
      "line": 68,
      "text": "between what we do with all"
    },
    {
      "line": 71,
      "text": "kinds of death and how we live."
    }
  ]
}